":"1516","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Wooley, Sedgemoor, Somerset, England":"Sedgemoor, Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Cherhill, Wiltshire, England":"Cherhill, Wiltshire, England","Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wheatley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Wheatley, for example in Essex, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire, Oxfordshire, and Yorkshire, or from Whatley in Somerset and Whateley in Warwickshire, all name of which are named with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘(woodland) clearing’. Compare   Whatley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wheetley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Wheatley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Watley","meanings":["English: variant of   Wheatley  ."]},{"name":"Wheatly","meanings":["English: variant of   Wheatley  ."]},{"name":"Wadley","meanings":["English: habitational name from numerous places. In southern England this can be derived from Wadley in Faringdon (Berkshire), or perhaps from Whatley (Somerset), Whateley in Kingsbury (Warwickshire), Wheatley (Oxfordshire), or Wheatley in Rayleigh (Essex), the latter of which often appears as <i>Watelegh</i> in the medieval records. The Berkshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The other placenames derive from Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>lēah</i>. Compare   Wheatley  . In some instances where the name originates from southeastern England, <i>Wadley</i> may alternatively be a post-medieval variant of   Wadlow  . In northern England, primarily Durham, this is a habitational name from Wadley in Witton le Wear (Durham). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i>, <i>Wadda</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>."]},{"name":"Whatley","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Somerset): variant of   Wheatley  . A habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, as for example Whatley in Somerset, Whately in Warwickshire, or any of the places mentioned under   Wheatley  ."]}]},{"name":"Jone","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Another spelling of Joan."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":58,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jone Wheatley was born in 1397, in Sedgemoor, Somerset, England, her father, William Wheatley, was 22 and her mother, Allice Piper, was 20. She married John Goddard about 1414, in Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1460, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1397–1460":"1397–1460","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1414–1420":"1414–1420","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1428–1516":"1428–1516","1375–1472":"1375–1472","1377–1435":"1377–1435","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1490":"1490","1414":"1414","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1420":"1420","1397":"1397","about 1414":"umbes 1414","1375":"1375","1428":"1428","1516":"1516","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wooley, Sedgemoor, Somerset, England":"Sedgemoor, Somers